<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1898-11-19T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1898-11-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="954" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d954">
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">White</persName>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1898-11-19"><hi rend="italic">November 19,
                                    1898</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 959.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: In view of a letter from the Secretary of
                            the Navy, dated the 15th instant, you are instructed to make, if
                            practicable, arrangements with the British Government permitting the
                            bringing to the United States of the torpedo boat <hi rend="italic">Somers</hi>, now stored at Falmouth, England, giving assurance that
                            in case of the resumption of hostilities with Spain this vessel will not
                            be made use of.</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>